        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94ed81f6e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>3:9.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Limitations on Panel&apos;s power—Transfer of entire claims only</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s authority permits it to transfer <ital>actions</ital> or <ital>claims
                    </ital> for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It does not, and cannot, order transfer of isolated factual or legal issues.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I028b0620680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] This
                        inherent limitation in the Panel&apos;s authority is important to ensure that the purposes of
                        the statute are met.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Although it may appear in some cases that the Panel violates this rule by ordering remand
                        of portions of actions,[<footnote.reference refid="I028b2d30680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            2</footnote.reference>] the Panel does so only with respect to entire claims.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel will not consider transferring a portion of a claim, such as the liability
                        questions, while remanding others, such as the damage issues.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s workload normally includes only civil actions pending in the district
                        courts.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel has recognized the authority to transfer adversary proceedings arising from
                        bankruptcy court cases.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I028b5440680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] The Panel
                        specifically considered the fact that bankruptcy court jurisdiction has <?page no="31"?> been recognized as part
                        of the district court jurisdiction, and adversary proceedings are therefore quite the same as
                        other cases in federal court.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>In practice this jurisdictional limitation on the Panel has not been of great significance
                        because the Panel has consistently relied on the transferee courts to make appropriate decisions
                        concerning the proper management of the cases transferred.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It appears unlikely that the Panel would have considered severance of issues and transfer
                        of only certain claims a worthwhile exercise of its jurisdiction even if its jurisdiction were
                        that broad.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I028b5441680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The only exception to the rule that only entire actions may be transferred is the
                        authority in the last clause of <cite.query w-src-number="0304913957" w-seq-number="00006"
                                                                    w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407"
                                                                    w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                                    ID="I10ba6c00680811e8aca4f6dd071ce3e8">28 U.S.C.A. §
                            1407(a)</cite.query>, which permits the Panel to separate and remand entire claims (of any
                        variety) to the district in which they were filed.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel has only ordered separation and remand in limited circumstances, and has not
                        used separation as a reason to deny transfer of the major portion of any cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Separation and remand are discussed in greater detail in §§ <cite.query w-ref-type="NA"
                                                                                                      w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:55"
                                                                                                      w-pub-number="185218"
                                                                                                      ID="I028c8cc0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            5:55
                        </cite.query> to  <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:57"
                                                      w-pub-number="185218" ID="I028c8cc1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            5:57</cite.query>.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
